 prepared under the guidance of Manuel F. Montes as part of the work programme of the United National Development Programme (UNDP) Asia-Pacific Trade and Investment Initiative. Comments from Manuel F. Montes and Swarnim Wagle are gratefully acknowledged. Research assistance of Bryn Gay and Gunalan Karuppanan and professional editing by Kay Kirby are noted with appreciation. The report also benefited from additional background inputs provided by the national consultants from three countries: Philippines (Joseph Francia); Nepal (Navin Dahal); and Sri Lanka (Ceylon Chamber of Commerce). An earlier (December 2005) version of the report was launched on 16 December 2005 at a Panel on Textiles and Clothing: One Year of Evidence from Asia organised by UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo on the sideline of the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference of the World Trade Organisation (WTO). Comments and suggestions from the Panel, in particular those of Munir Ahmad and Mustafizur Rahman, are gratefully acknowledged and suitably incorporated in this revised version of the report.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e3d4a78f-c961-4a2c-bce4-ed8bd971f74f": {"__data__": {"id_": "e3d4a78f-c961-4a2c-bce4-ed8bd971f74f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7125ee8ddb89d15ec54e37f9fe257c50560a8f1d408adb9fbaf26a7fbcbb3e97"}, "2": {"node_id": "5351c4a8-f807-4919-9141-0aa4bd381d0f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a86b825225e4b0a9099fa5f7af72ccbc7054c0a2c3c5037d63bfa6f949e42097"}}, "hash": "990955fccbb19f40b6ef70eef4142a59e41e6425f24abcb2b715b75a914ccda0", "text": "5 Acronyms and Abbreviations ACP African, Caribbean, and Pacific AD Anti-dumping AGOA Africa Growth and Opportunity Act ASEAN Association of South East Asian Nations ATC Agreement on Textiles and Clothing CBI Caribbean Basin Initiative CBPTA Caribbean Basin Trade Partnership Agreement CEEC Central and Eastern European Countries DDA Doha Development Agenda DR-CAFTA Dominican Republican-Central America Free Trade Agreement EBA Everything But Arms EFTA European Free Trade Area EPZ Export Processing Zones EU European Union ETE Export Tariff Equivalents FDI Foreign Direct Investment FTA Free Trade Agreement GATT General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade GSP Generalised System of Preferences GSTP Generalised System of Trade Preferences ILO International Labour Organisation IMF International Monetary Fund LDC Least Developed Country MDGs Millennium Development Goals MFA Multi Fibre Arrangement MFN Most Favoured Nation NAFTA North American Free Trade Area NAMA Non-Agricultural Market Access 6 NCTO National Council of Textile Organisations PDR People\u2019s Democratic Republic RMG Ready Made Garment ROO Rules of Origin SAARC South Asian Association for Regional Co-operation SCM Subsidies and Countervailing Measures T&C Textiles and Clothing UNCTAD United Nations Conference on Trade and Development UNDP United Nations Development Programme UNDP RCC United Nations Development Programme Regional Centre in Colombo UNLDC UN Conference of Least Developed Countries US United States USA United States of America USITC United States International Trade Commission USP Unique Selling Proposition USTR United States Trade Representative WTO World Trade Organisation Flying Colours, Broken Threads 7 I. Introduction The textiles and clothing (T&C) sector hosts a substantial share of manufacturing jobs in many developing countries in Asia. Millions of people, most of them women, now work in the sector, and many were elevated from a subsistence level due to employment opportunities offered by this sector. It also is a sector that contributed to greater export performance of developing countries, thus generating foreign exchange earnings. Full implementation of the World Trade Organisation (WTO) Agreement on Textiles and Clothing (ATC) on 1 January 2005 ended 40 years of quota-based trade in the sector, \u201cmanaged\u201d through non-transparent bilateral deals known as the Multi Fibre Arrangement (MFA). These deals violated the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4b569ca0-076b-413d-975e-0ca667e0153e": {"__data__": {"id_": "4b569ca0-076b-413d-975e-0ca667e0153e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "218150d5df79650ee8771c38d4516d47fc4728e34bba9ba28d54caf67bcc6a8c"}, "3": {"node_id": "be4a12df-e7db-4337-ade4-c0b797005f5c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fcdf8a8c1662b0f5543c57f3a2d693904639ec8e2ebcca9fc6f23917edf85169"}}, "hash": "fcca2515961ce9c72b8d5f7fad99bc9065d7d848154c0ae9ac16089f8ae042a5", "text": "two fundamental principles of the WTO: most favoured nation (MFN),1 and limits on imposition of quantitative restrictions.2 Now that the T&C sector has become a part of the regular WTO discipline like other goods, no derogation shall be allowed to this sector. Quota limits, when they existed, directly restrained the exports of large developing countries. Many Least Developed Countries (LDCs) that had been able to expand production and obtain access to major markets under the MFA now face the prospect of major structural and socio-economic dislocation. The elimination of quotas has been expected to lead to major shifts in trade and investment flows. As competition in this sector intensifies, the most competitive players are likely to further consolidate their positions at the expense of the least competitive ones. It is feared that this will result in significant employment loss in countries belonging to the latter category, where enhancing competitiveness has remained elusive. In order to assess the human development impact of quota elimination, the UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo (UNDP RCC) launched a Textiles and Clothing Trade Flows Tracking System in 12 selected Asian countries (hereafter, the \u201cAsian 12\u201d) in May 2005. The Asian 12 consists of: Bangladesh, Cambodia, China, India, Indonesia, Lao People\u2019s Democratic Republic (PDR), Nepal, Pakistan, the Philippines, Sri Lanka, Thailand, and Viet Nam. These countries can be grouped into four categories: (1) countries with large production capability in both textile and apparel production (China, India); (2) countries that have limited production capability in both textile and apparel production (Indonesia, Pakistan, Thailand, Viet Nam); (3) middle-income countries that mainly have apparel production capability (Philippines, Sri Lanka); and (4) LDCs (Bangladesh, Cambodia, Lao PDR, Nepal). In cooperation with national consultants in participating countries, UNDP RCC established the tracking system with the objectives of monitoring trade flows as well as key variables including shifts in employment patterns and international price trends in the T&C sector. Reports analysing the data and highlighting major trends are being published quarterly. This initiative complements a sub-project at UNDP RCC that aims at 1 Article I of General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). 2 Article XI of GATT. One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 8 identifying national and regional policy options to address the possible negative economic and social impacts of the phasing out of quotas in 12 countries. A Tracking Report titled Trade Flows and Recent Developments in Textiles and Clothing in the Asia-Pacific was published in September 2005 and presented at the Geneva Dialogue on Trade Policy and Human Development, co-organised by UNDP RCC and held in Yverdon-les-Bains, Switzerland from 29 September to 1 October 2005. Based on suggestions from resource persons and participants at the Geneva Dialogue, an updated, revised version of the Report was published in October 2005. The publication was the first attempt to make the Report public, with a view to provoking wider discussion on the human development implications of the phasing out of T&C quotas. This Report, when first published in December 2005, updated several information contained in September/October Report, including analyses of several policy questions on the basis of most recent data and information available. The report is based on import data \u2013 from two major markets, namely the United States (US) and European Union (EU) for a period of nine months after the phase out of quotas (January \u2013 September 2005) \u2013 as well as countries trade data, where available.3 Another important value addition to this report is that it also incorporates, where appropriate, findings from the field visits conducted by the authors in four LDCs \u2013 Bangladesh, Cambodia, Lao PDR and Nepal \u2013between October and December 2005. The report was further updated in January 2006 to incorporate the decisions made at the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference of the WTO and comments and suggestions made by the participants during a Panel on Textile and Clothing: One Year of Evidence from Asia organised by UNDP RCC in Hong Kong on 16 December 2005. Other relevant data, such as employment, flows of investment into the T&C sector, the level of technology transfer and the skill levels of workers, are hard to obtain at the disaggregated level. Therefore, a full description of human development implications of the phasing out of quotas is not possible yet.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "be4a12df-e7db-4337-ade4-c0b797005f5c": {"__data__": {"id_": "be4a12df-e7db-4337-ade4-c0b797005f5c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": 