 shares of the Asian 12 and other regions that have trade agreements with the United States for imports of T&C products for the period of 2003, 2004, January-September 2004 and January-September 2005. Similarly, percentage shares of the Asian 12 and top trading partners for EU imports of T&C, textiles, and clothing products are displayed in Tables A-2a, A-2b, and A-2c respectively. A comparison of import figures for the first three quarters of 2005 with the corresponding period in 2004 shows that the share of US imports from the Asian 12 increased from 41.5 percent to 50.3 percent in value terms and from 41.9 percent to 50.5 percent in volume terms (Tables A-1a and A-1b). In contrast, regions that have trade agreements with the United States have lost their shares in US imports of T&C products, in spite of their preferential market access. The share of Caribbean Basin Initiative (CBI) countries plus Mexico in the US market declined from 21.5 percent to 19.2 percent in value terms and from 22.2 percent to 20.0 percent in volume terms. Shares of CBI plus Mexico were 23.0 percent and 22.7 percent in value and volume terms respectively in 2003. The share of African countries under the African Growth and Opportunity Act (AGOA) \u2013 which are the beneficiaries of generous preferential market access in the United States \u2013 also declined from 2.0 to 1.6 percent in value terms and from 1.6 percent to 1.3 percent in volume terms. The share of the Asian 12 in EU imports is even larger than US imports (Table A-2a). During the period January-September 2004, the share of the Asian 12 in EU imports of T&C products was 45.2 percent in value terms and 48.5 percent in volume terms. For the same period of 2005, the share has increased to 52.0 percent in value terms and 54.1 percent in volume terms. The surge in imports from the Asian 12 is more pronounced in clothing products than in textiles (Tables A-2b and A-2c). While overall EU imports of clothing products increased by 5.4 percent in value terms and 9.4 percent in volume terms in the first three quarters of 2005 as compared to the same period of 2004, the growth rate of EU imports from the Asian 12 exceeded 20 percent in both value and volume terms. The Asian 12 now control 55.4 percent of total EU imports of clothing product in value terms and 67.4 percent in volume terms. In contrast, the percentage share of the Asian 12 in EU imports of textiles is 37.5 percent in value terms and 38.1 percent in volume terms for the first three quarters of 2005.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ab112faf-30a4-41aa-8dc2-ef203fc2d525": {"__data__": {"id_": "ab112faf-30a4-41aa-8dc2-ef203fc2d525", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "259f7f3a4a1a7ef906c98c75ad5238f5fa0b4c6a350bacc2160ad3bbbf625d35"}, "2": {"node_id": "9d5829b3-da65-4feb-8ffb-f023bdd84acf", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0db97e72f10bffa9903e388d84395404d91119cc89e46f876b73d3938a0b3aa0"}}, "hash": "50419aee51c2766a89cfaa440f15a74e691af88c1d38fc6ba4646dc5de84cc49", "text": "EU imports of textiles are less skewed as compared to EU imports of clothing products. One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 10 Country Specific Analysis China is the leading contributor to the growth of the US and EU imports of T&C products from", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d0015ebe-32f9-4b06-b30d-d81f54bf4f90": {"__data__": {"id_": "d0015ebe-32f9-4b06-b30d-d81f54bf4f90", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "160797522280b97249c42ff6d0dc4f6c215fb038f876a847194c43909d78bc42"}}, "hash": "160797522280b97249c42ff6d0dc4f6c215fb038f876a847194c43909d78bc42", "text": "the Asian 12. China\u2019s share to total US imports of T&C products, already about 15 percent in 2003, continues to increase. More than a quarter of all US T&C imports in the \ufb01rst three quarters of 2005 came from China. Similarly, EU imports of T&C products from China rose from 21 percent in January-September 2004 to 28-30 percent in 2005. However, moderate increases in China\u2019s share in EU imports of textiles indicate that the growth of China\u2019s exports of clothing products is overwhelming. In the \ufb01rst three quarters of 2005, China\u2019s shares in EU imports of textiles were 18.2 percent in value terms and 14.3 percent in volume terms, whereas China\u2019s share in EU imports of clothing products are 32.9 percent in value terms and 39.8 percent in volume terms. Chinese exports now account for 60 percent of the Asian 12 clothing exports to the EU. Among the Asian 12, Bangladesh, Cambodia, India, Indonesia, and Pakistan also increased their exports to the United States as well as their shares of US imports of T&C products. However, among these countries, only India managed to increase its exports of clothing products to the EU at the same time. EU imports of textiles from India slightly declined.4 Besides China and India, all other Asian 12 countries experienced declines in their exports of clothing products to the EU. Among other top trade partners of the EU, only Turkey succeeded to protect its previous gains so far, thanks to its steady rise in clothing exports to the EU. Turkey, the second- largest T&C trade partner of the EU after China, increased its exports of clothing products to the EU by 4.1 percent in value terms and 3.2 percent in volume terms. Similar to the case of India however, EU imports of textiles from Turkey slightly declined. EU imports of clothing products from other EU trade partners (Romania, Tunisia, Morocco) experienced nearly a 10 percent decline. The fall in EU imports from other Asian countries (Hong Kong SAR, South Korea) are more severe. For example, EU imports of clothing products from South Korea plummeted by more than 50 percent in both value and volume terms. US and EU imports from Lao PDR, Nepal, the Philippines and Viet Nam, as well as these four countries\u2019 share in US and EU imports, declined in both value and volume terms. The declining trend in US imports of T&C products from these countries had started even before the elimination of quotas on 1 January 2005, but this is a matter of serious concern. Reduction rates of Lao PDR and Nepal in the US market and that of the Philippines in the EU market, in percentage terms, are all double-digit - as high as 40 percent in the \ufb01rst nine months of 2005 compared to the same period of 2004. 4 Table A-4d shows that a large decline in the volume of EU imports of textiles from India stems from man made staple \ufb01bres (HS 55). In terms of value, EU imports declined by 15 million Euro in cotton textiles (HS 52) and 30 million Euro in man made staple \ufb01bres. Flying Colours, Broken Threads 11 Products Liberalised in 2005 EU imports of T&C products liberalised in 2005 are summarised in Table A-3, which indicates that the phase-out of the end-loaded quotas has contributed to increased trade, with the increasing share of the EU T&C market being captured by Asian countries. To the extent that quota restrictions had an impact on large potential exporters, an increase in exports was expected after the removal of quotas. However, the only beneficiaries of liberalisation among the Asian 12 are China and India. In the first three quarters of 2005, EU imports of Chinese T&C products liberalised in 2005 increased by 144.7 percent in volume terms compared to the same period of 2004. Despite a 20 percent decline in the average unit prices of Chinese products, the value of EU imports rose by 95.2 percent. In 2004 Turkey was the largest exporter to the EU in the categories of T&C products that were liberalised in 2005. Although EU imports of such products from Turkey also increased in both value and volume terms, China is now the leading exporter of T&C products liberalised in 2005, due to a surge of Chinese imports. India, like the case of Turkey, also increased its share of EU imports of T&C products liberalised in 2005 both in value and volume terms, as well as in average unit prices. The elimination of quotas did not bring increases in the volume of exports to other countries in the EU market.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8b375a7f-f43b-49ae-a29d-b584a32d40e7": {"__data__": {"id_": "8b375a7f-f43b-49ae-a29d-b584a32d40e7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fcd76ab77b67e66faf1e5f26733cf3ff26593a0efcdf9bc5a60481c6431404fe"}}, "hash": "fcd76ab77b67e66faf1e5f26733cf3ff26593a0efcdf9bc5a60481c6431404fe", "text": "III. Policy Implications In this section, we attempt to discuss policy issues relevant from a human development perspective as far as the T&C sector of the Asian 12 is concerned. While some directly emanate from the analysis of data, others draw on recent developments in the sector as documented in the literature or on the basis of discussions with stakeholders during visits by the authors to four Asian LDCs (Bangladesh, Cambodia, Lao PDR, Nepal). Impact on Employment and Poverty \u201c[L]eading factories pay above-average wages on good contracts, achieve high productivity, and so require little or no overtime, but these examples are the exception, not the norm\u201d (Oxfam, 2004: 58). The overall volume as well as value of exports from China and India increased in both the US and EU markets with higher volume of exports expected to lead to employment growth. Increases in volume also could be possible with improved labour productivity and technology upgrading, even if the number of workers remains the same. However, since the figures being compared in this report are between two consecutive years, the developing countries in question are not expected to make a massive leap in productivity within such a short time span. Because data on employment are hard to come by, taking export volume as a proxy for employment we will not be hugely off the mark. Such a clear-cut picture does not emerge in the case of countries like Pakistan and Indonesia, which have seen their exports to the US market increase but suffered setbacks in the EU market. For example, Pakistan\u2019s exports to the United States increased by 10.2 One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 12 percent in value terms and 13.4 percent in volume, but exports to the EU declined by 12.8 percent and 2.7 percent respectively (Table A-4h). In the case of Indonesia, exports to the United States increased by 16.7 percent in value terms and 13.4 percent in volume terms, while exports to the EU declined \u2013 17.5 percent in value and 11.1 percent in volume (Table A-4e). It is equally difficult to draw any inferences on the employment situation in a country like Bangladesh, which has been able to hold on to its past gain in terms of overall value of exports (Table A-4a), but has seen overall volume decline by 3.4 percent during the first three quarters of 2005 against the same period of 2004. It can, therefore, be suspected that there have been some employment losses in Bangladesh. There is yet another factor that has to be considered because employment intensity of the two sub-sectors, namely knitted and woven garments, differ markedly. The woven garment sector, which falls under the Chapter 62 of the Harmonised Commodity Description and Coding System (HS), is labour-intensive and not highly demanding in terms of skills requirements. Accordingly, it employs huge numbers of unskilled labour, most of them women. Therefore, the percentage of women working in the woven sector is much higher than that in the knitted garment sector (HS 61). Bangladeshi employment losses are likely to fall upon women because the overall volume of US and EU woven garment imports declined by about 6 percent in the first nine months of 2005. Two LDCs analysed by this tracking report, Nepal and Lao PDR, saw both value and volume of its exports decline in both important markets. According to a news report quoting the Garment Association of Nepal, Nepalese garment exports to the US market \u2013 where 80 percent of such Nepalese exports are destined \u2013 declined by 42 percent during the 11 months period of 2005, compared to the corresponding period last year.5 As a result, more than 60 percent of garment factories have closed and nearly 50,000 people have lost jobs. A number of meetings held in Nepal with various stakeholders in October 2005, including the government, private sector, trade unions and civil society followed by a factory visit, confirmed this trend in the context of Nepal. Currently, only 15-30 factories are estimated to be operating. Even among those firms, hundreds of workers already have been laid off. As a result, the size of operation is very slim compared to that of 2004. Many garment workers, especially women, are contract workers, and Nepalese garment workers were no exception. In developing countries and LDCs where alternate sources of employment are difficult to find, and where safety nets such as unemployment insurance are non-existent or not implemented in earnest, these contract workers suddenly fall into poverty if they lose their jobs. Another problem found with the lack of social safety", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8a0545f3-16b3-4db5-9162-bab69775c082": {"__data__": {"id_": "8a0545f3-16b3-4db5-9162-bab69775c082", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c540e0ed98c6060b9a3328ec6a87a9309ff0de0c7eba9467b416c039cc8f48bf"}, "3": {"node_id": "0d9d4df8-d1f7-40dd-b7fb-ed4582bbbfa4", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "97b0f83276b1f7e1166e53e47e870a7d122835df70b3d6eeee1bcc896283752d"}}, "hash": "2cf6de90018e3bd6522b0d1d8fc3221ee02b86fd52492c448cc65cc9c422ea2c", "text": "nets is that there exists no official ways of tracking where retrenched workers go after they lose jobs. Recent studies (e.g., Balakrishnan, 2002) indicate that more female workers have no choice but to accept informal and home-based work, which entails fewer legal rights and benefits than the formal sector. In the case of Lao PDR, there were 57 garment factories and 39 small sub-contract factories (Tan, 2005), where about 27,000 people, mostly young women from rural 5 The report is available from Kantipur Online, http://www.kantipuronline.com/kolnews.php?&nid=59106 Flying Colours, Broken Threads 13 villages, were working and sending remittances to their families. So far, a few factories have shut down. In cities, employment opportunities for women who are ethnic minorities and/or with less education are limited. Low factory wages have contributed to an increase in prostitution: Many female factory workers feel compelled to earn extra money for remittance by moonlighting in restaurants or nightclubs where they may be sexually exploited by customers.6 Women garment workers face the cultural stigma of being considered promiscuous. While the migration to neighbouring countries, especially Thailand is on the rise, growing trade in the region bring foreign truck drivers and traders to Lao PDR. Currently HIV/AIDS prevalence is still low overall (UNAIDS, 2005). However, growing population mobility between this small landlocked country and five much larger neighbours with more serious epidemics implies that this low rate will not continue for long. Even in countries where export growth has been robust, a painful story is that increased exports do not necessarily translate into better wages or working conditions. For example, as documented by Verma (2005) in the case of India, employment increased by 113 percent in the second half of 1990s, while export of textiles increased by 143 percent. Per- capita incomes in this sector, by contrast, increased by a mere 20 percent, due to a huge population of unemployed people \u2013 who were willing to work at any wage level. Employment also has become increasingly casualised over the time. More jobs have been created for women, but conditions of employment have not improved and in some cases, may even have worsened (Jha and Karthikeyan, 2003). Another factor responsible for this trend, which is becoming more visible in the quota-free world, is that increased pressure to reduce production costs so as to remain competitive tends to make entrepreneurs compromise on wage and working conditions. Evidence from Bangladesh, Philippines and India suggest that Governments there have either introduced, or are in the process of, amending legislation to exempt the garment sector from minimum wage requirements or allow women to work in night shifts, under certain conditions (ILO, 2005: 35). In China, where export growth has been impressive, the situation is not very different. Guangdong province of southern coastal China is an industrial hub producing for global consumption of ready made garments (RMGs). Millions in this province are temporary rural migrant workers. According to Chinese labour laws, a five-day work week should not exceed 40 hours, with a limit of overtime work of 36 hours each month. However, these employment contracts have involved hundreds hours of overtime work, with payment of wages in arrears and underpayment for female migrant garment workers from rural villages (Chan 2005a, 2005b). One reason garment workers are forced to work for long hours (90 to 120 hours a week), is to meet \u201cjust-in-time\u201d delivery of products and shorter lead times from buyers (Oxfam, 2004). As a result of long hours of work without a rest day, female workers in garment sectors face poor health conditions. Chan (2005b) discusses that the number of labour disputes, as well as the number of employees involved in labour disputes, has increased over time; by 2002, there were 184,116 arbitrated cases. The more workers learn about labor laws in the process of collective bargaining, the higher wages and better working conditions are demanded. Comments from female garment workers involved in a collective protest to obtain back pay confirms the 6 CEDAW report cited in ADB (2004). One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 14 relocation of manufacturing facilities to an interior province, such as Jiangxi, as most likely to avoid labour disputes as well as employ cheaper labour.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0d9d4df8-d1f7-40dd-b7fb-ed4582bbbfa4": {"__data__": {"id_": "0d9d4df8-d1f7-40dd-b7fb-ed4582bbbfa4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Develo