{"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "27f6fe047793b1f3ab090f8749f5ee83de435bdb174ddd33fae668f184b1becc"}, "3": {"node_id": "fb4f41a0-0c0b-48f0-a39b-57bf0466bdb1", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9b55ad33c527f68d3d0e6407aa3946bd06f8e7afb63b51f71ca7a571f01d3bb2"}}, "hash": "6aeb46ebcb0fd7568efd5e2a2797eab223d5bb9e217493617340004d6d4ac7c3", "text": "found that the average monthly income of female garment workers in export processing zones (EPZ) on the peri-urban outskirts of Dhaka was 3,014 Takas, while female workers in garment factories within Dhaka, who make up the bulk of workers in the export sector, receive 1,706 Takas per month. Even so it is argued that the average monthly earnings of Dhaka garment workers were roughly double the monthly per capita \u201cpoverty line\u201d income (725 Takas in urban areas and 635 Takas in rural areas in 2000); however, the same survey shows that 23 percent of Dhaka garment workers have experienced food shortages in the past year. A comparison of hourly wages among EPZ garment workers, Dhaka garment workers, self-employed workers, and other wage workers in domestic service or at construction sites is not possible, since the hours of work are unknown from these survey results. However, effects on health is more frequently cited as the main drawback of employment by Dhaka garment workers (24 percent) than self-employed workers (14 percent) and EPZ garment workers (9 percent). This might imply the long hours of work and/or an unhealthy work environment. Regarding working conditions, only 1 percent of Dhaka garment workers have received contract letters, whereas 64 percent of EPZ garment workers have received it. Female garment workers in Dhaka city factories are extremely vulnerable during the downturn of production and are likely to be the first to be laid off. Turning to Cambodia, that country seems to be doing much better on the employment front compared to Bangladesh, because not only did total exports increase by 8 percent in value terms, but the volume of its exports increased by 30 percent in the first nine months of 2005 (Table A-4b). Cambodia\u2019s strides into the T&C sector, like in the case of most other LDCs, were fuelled by quota restrictions imposed on other Asian countries. This sector was successful in attracting a large amount of foreign direct investment (FDI),8 mainly from East Asian countries, with FDI totaling US$ 27.6 million in 2002. Export volume increased from US$20 million in 1995 to US$1.5 billion in 2004 and employment in the clothing industry amounted to 270,000 workers in 2005 (ILO, 2005a: 21). New data show, as of November 2005, 43 factories had opened this year, 279,000 were employed as agreement workers, and wages had remained constant at about $72 per month (Wasson, 2005). The country is heavily dependent on exports of clothing products, which constitute 80 percent of total merchandise exports. Up to 85-90 percent of these workers are women supporting between 1 million and 1.5 million family members by sending 10 to 40 percent of their income home regularly (ILO, 2005a; Fitzgerald, 2004; Sim, 2004; USAID, 2005b). In a less diversified economy like Cambodia\u2019s, garment workers have few alternative employment opportunities. Any losses in employment could therefore have a chain 7 As per Bangladesh\u2019s macroeconomic assessment of 2004 conducted by ADB, inflation (measured by consumer price index) rate was 5.8 percent for 2004 and is forecast to 7 percent in 2005, 6 percent in 2006 and 5 percent in 2007. See ADB (2005). 8 UNCTAD FDI database, as quoted in WTO (2005): 94. Flying Colours, Broken Threads 15 reaction on the poverty situation in the rural areas. Fortunately, the situation has not deteriorated as per the data available for the first three quarters of 2005. Overall, T&C exports from the Asian 12, led by China, are doing well so far. However, thousands of workers already have lost jobs in Nepal and Lao PDR, where the quota elimination has severely hit. In other countries where jobs are still kept, the growth of production and exports often does not benefit workers in terms of wages and working conditions; rather conditions worsen. Countries where low labour costs represent the prime competitive advantage start getting squeezed out of the game. As in the case of Cambodia (discussed later), improving labour standards can have a positive impact on export growth of T&C products. Empowering female workers in export industries to improve their working conditions helps to promote equity, and equity can in turn engender productivity and sustainability (UNDP RCC, 2005a). Changing Buyers\u2019 Preferences The T&C market has been transformed into a buyers\u2019 market, with a small number of large retailers dominating the sector.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fb4f41a0-0c0b-48f0-a39b-57bf0466bdb1": {"__data__": {"id_": "fb4f41a0-0c0b-48f0-a39b-57bf0466bdb1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "27f6fe047793b1f3ab090f8749f5ee83de435bdb174ddd33fae668f184b1becc"}, "2": {"node_id": "dd33f92c-9e02-48c8-af13-b9f9d884bb46", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6aeb46ebcb0fd7568efd5e2a2797eab223d5bb9e217493617340004d6d4ac7c3"}}, "hash": "9b55ad33c527f68d3d0e6407aa3946bd06f8e7afb63b51f71ca7a571f01d3bb2", "text": "The economic power of large retailers, predominantly in developed countries, has increased substantially over the last few years (WTO, 2005a: 5). In the United States, for example, the 29 biggest retailers account for 98 percent of sales (UNDP RCC, 2005b). The trend now is toward greater product specialisation, brand-name and market segmentation. These large", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e0ad0034-b3dd-492b-83c9-840aac6a3e88": {"__data__": {"id_": "e0ad0034-b3dd-492b-83c9-840aac6a3e88", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5b073a00f5c373584040d1033fa721271cf406eaea9b32d789a568284863533d"}}, "hash": "5b073a00f5c373584040d1033fa721271cf406eaea9b32d789a568284863533d", "text": "retailers collect market information about the latest trends in styles and tastes, and their integration of this information gives them considerable leverage in dealing with suppliers (Kelegama and Weeraratne, 2005). The market power of buyers appears huge; it may have even given them the leverage to extract concessions from suppliers, in the form of reduced prices, and to pocket the difference without passing lower prices on to consumers. As per the data of the EU (see Table A-3), in the first nine months of the quota-free world average prices reduced by 5.1 percent for products liberalised in 2005, yet retail prices for garments have remained stable, with only fractional changes up or down since the beginning of 2005 (European Commission, 2005). It also appears that the quota rent, or Export Tariff Equivalents (ETE), discussed below in the context of price competition, is now transferred to retailers. A further investigation into the existence of abuse of market power, if any, from an industrial organisation perspective will help design a suitable competition-policy response to this problem. Because of this power, it is the buyers\u2019 preference that is going to shape market response in the exporting countries. Although price and quality used to be the only two variables, buyer preferences these days represent an interplay of various factors, of which five remain important.9 Cost factor: The cost of final delivery of goods into the warehouse of the buyer is what primarily interests the majority of buyers. Some countries may have the cost advantage 9 See also Kelegama and Weeraratne (2005): 330. One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 16 due to cheap labour,10 but may have higher costs of delivery due to bureaucratic red tape, dilapidated infrastructure and/or lack of trade facilitation measures. These countries may not be the first choice of buyers. There are, however, exceptions to this rule: For example, those buyers who are extremely conscious about brand image and cater to the clientele who are not price-sensitive may not worry much about the cost factor. Critical mass: Buyers will be reluctant to place orders with producers with a small share in the world market. According to this view, countries like India and China, with large integrated production capacity and the ability to deliver huge quantity, are likely to be preferred by buyers. In Asia-Pacific a very few countries like China, India and Pakistan will be the prime beneficiaries if this scenario prevails. Supporting this hypothesis, the US Department of Commerce estimates the number of countries from which major items will be sourced will drop by 50 percent in 2005, and to 25 percent of current levels by 2010 (UNDP RCC, 2005b: 23). Risk spreading: A possible scenario opposing the critical mass sentiment is the risk- spreading argument. Buyers, desirous to maintain uninterrupted supply, would like to diversify the sources from which they import T&C products. Since events such as terrorist attacks, spread of contagious diseases like SARS and avian flu, or even reimposition of quota, could significantly disrupt the smooth flow of products, buyers could prefer to source products from several locations. For example, according to the US International Trade Commission: \u201cTo reduce the risk of sourcing from only one country, the US importers also plan to expand trade relationships with other low-cost countries alternative to China\u201d (USITC, 2004). Total solution providers: Buyers\u2019 preferences are likely to be tilted in favour of suppliers that can cover all stages of the value chain in production, ranging from product design to input sourcing, manufacturing, packaging and shipping of the final product. This is because buyers do not want to coordinate several activities and engage their precious human resources in the follow-up of various stages of the process. Though this would mean that countries with the ready availability of domestic inputs and human resources are likely to meet this requirement, countries that can \u201cslice up\u201d the value chain, organising production in various countries depending on the level of specialisation also can be winners in this scenario. Ethical concerns: Though this is an emerging area, pressures from consumer groups in industrialised countries, including boycotting of products manufactured in sweatshops or in environmentally-unfriendly way have brought ethical concerns into the decision- making matrix of the buyers. Most buyers have themselves developed a \u201ccode of conduct\u201d that they want all their suppliers to comply with. This includes issues such as working conditions, workers\u2019 health and safety, minimum wages, maximum working hours and overtime. The authors observed in the factories they visited in Bangladesh and Nepal in October 2005 that such requirements were not only fully met, but", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6c1dc6ed-cf87-474a-886c-e9441b5745f1": {"__data__": {"id_": "6c1dc6ed-cf87-474a-886c-e9441b5745f1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6927f6dfb6b63b08d78a8835e80ea79542d6ceaef49ad7f4824e31c9e7a120ff"}, "3": {"node_id": "d0095a1f-dd86-4f53-8257-1b017ab8cbb3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9f8b35cab941f87522383833bad331a455237420eb43e1cd313d74b1bec9f2c8"}}, "hash": "b93d2dc15903f48a91ea093b08cb2435bfbaf4125e382c344c0aeff3405fe85e", "text": "were written and 10 However, labour costs as a percentage of total value of export is very low in most countries: 7.5 percent in Bangladesh (Razzaque, 2005); 15 percent in Cambodia (WTO, 2005a); and 29.17 percent in Nepal (Shakya, 2005). Moreover, from the human development perspective, it is neither ethical nor desirable to improve export performance by maintaining low wages (or poverty). Flying Colours, Broken Threads 17 visibly displayed for the sake of transparency. Nonetheless, though national laws and international conventions deal with these issues, most developing countries have not implemented them, either due to the pressure from industry groups or simply lack of resources. However, Cambodia, an LDC, has successfully made improved labour standards as its \u201cunique selling proposition\u201d (USP) in the industrialised-countries market, which will be discussed later. Lao PDR, another LDC, is planning to make environmental standards (such as eco-labels) as its USP for the EU market.11 It should be noted, however, that having a USP does not guarantee that export orders will last forever. For example, the Nepalese RMG factory that authors visited had not received any orders from major US retailers since the first quarter of 2005 although it had been following the \u201ccode of conduct\u201d given by retailers for several years. Often being a sub- contractor or having an international agent receive consolidated orders works as a disadvantage because lack of loyalty puts producers in a weaker position while bargaining with retailers. The sudden withdrawal of retailers from garment production in Nepal is also confirmed at the factories that previously had direct ordering systems with US retailers. Extent of Price Competition When quota restrictions were in place, the export prices of textile and clothing products were higher from countries restrained by quotas. The ETE12 of the quotas on textile and clothing for China and India were as high as 33-34 percent (Nordas, 2004). This provided sufficient cushion to accept orders from the buyers in the post-quota era at prices significantly lower than those prevailing until the end of 2004. Asian countries \u2013 which are the highest performers in the post-quota regime \u2013 were most restricted by quotas, comprising eight out of 10 countries most restricted by textile quotas and all 10 countries most restricted by clothing quotas (ILO, 2005a:4). Due to increased competition in the post-quota regime, prices have fallen sharply in the case of most of these countries. It was predicted that countries with higher ETE would be able to resort to price undercutting13 without their bottom line being affected. Although it is difficult to discern a particular trend, an analysis of EU import data for the period January \u2013 September 2005 suggests that prices have fallen on the whole by 5.1 percent. 11 Based on the discussions of the authors with the officials of International Trade Centre, 23 November 2005. 12 In the literature, the measure that is most widely used to infer about the restrictiveness of an MFA quota is known as the \u201cexport tax equivalent\u201d (ETE). An export quota may be considered as an export tax in its restrictive impact on exports. In order to export, a firm in a quota constrained country has to purchase a quota and the price of a quota per unit of exports is then equivalent in its impact to an export tax of the same magnitude. The more restrictive a quota is, the higher the tax will be. In other words, The ETE represents a rent as a per cent of the price of the export product. See Razzaque (2005): 30. 13 Lower prices in markets without quotas do not imply that total revenues decline. They could even increase with increased output \u2013 and possibly employment. One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 18 Table 1: Average Fall in Prices in the EU of T&C products Liberalised in 2005 Country Ranking (Clothing quotas) Ranking (Textile quotas) Change in prices in the EU market China (including Hong Kong and Macau) 1 1 - 20.2% Korea 2 5 - 0.1% Bangladesh 4 8 - 8.6% Viet Nam 5 7 0.2% Indonesia 6 6 -5.8% India 8 3 8.6% Pakistan 9 2 -11.1% Philippines 10 N/A -6.2% Thailand 11 4 -9.0% Source: ILO (2005a): 3-4, for the first and second columns. See Table A-3 for the third column.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d0095a1f-dd86-4f53-8257-1b017ab8cbb3": {"__data__": {"id_": "d0095a1f-dd86-4f53-8257-1b017ab8cbb3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6927f6dfb6b63b08d78a8835e80ea79542d6ceaef49ad7f4824e31c9e7a120ff"}, "2": {"node_id": "6c1dc6ed-cf87-474a-886c-e9441b5745f1", "node