metre, falling over 90 percent.15 Due to lack of information on the cost structure of these companies, it is difficult to ascertain whether firms are simply reducing prices within the 14 For example, two shirts belonging to same HS code (even at 12 digit level) can have different costs, depending on the use of materials, design and time spent on stitching them. 15 EmergingTextiles.com (2005a), http://www.emergingtextiles.com/?q=art&s=051121Dmark&r=free, Flying Colours, Broken Threads 19 ETEs of their earlier quotas, or whether price reductions have started eating into profit margins. Other reports point out that heightened competition has resulted in cuts of up to 47 percent in prices, such as in the case of EU import of pullover sweaters (USAID, 2005). When such cut-throat competition becomes the order of the day, countries to be worst hit are those that did not have higher quota rent in the first place. Since the imposition of quotas was directly correlated to the competitiveness of the country, it is the least competitive exporters that will be affected by falling prices. Most LDCs fall into this category. Threats of Trade Remedy Measures Highly competitive suppliers like China, India and Pakistan can be subjected to trade remedy measures such as anti-dumping, countervailing and safeguard measures in order to contain their domination in certain markets. Incorporated into the multilateral trading system to create a level playing field for domestic industries by protecting them against \u201cunfair\u201d foreign competition, these instruments have been captured by the protectionist lobby in the industrialised countries. Developing countries too have now started using these measures for protectionist purposes. Of the three types of trade remedy measures, anti-dumping is the most pernicious because of the ease with which it can be applied. Moreover, anti-dumping measures can be applied to targeted firms in targeted countries, almost with absolute impunity. T&C products have been and will continue to be the major target of anti-dumping investigations. Bed linen has been one of the most targeted products by the EU, with exports from India, Pakistan, Turkey and Thailand already facing the brunt. One reasons for the decline in Pakistan\u2019s export under HS 63 to the EU market has been the continued imposition anti-dumping duty on the bed linen.16 The volume of EU imports of bed linen (HS 630210-630239) from Pakistan in the first nine months of 2005 against the same period of 2004 declined by 2.2 percent.17 Realising the potential threat of China as a major exporter of T&C in the post-quota era, WTO member countries got three unconventional provisions ingeniously incorporated in the latter\u2019s Protocol of Accession to the WTO.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "85e70b8b-e566-42c9-bc43-28dde4f00ce2": {"__data__": {"id_": "85e70b8b-e566-42c9-bc43-28dde4f00ce2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ee5ec58b0802ffefeed2fca0b3428664516f74737901a609e3af8a3b7a1563b3"}, "2": {"node_id": "05679634-5a2e-4cf6-8bc3-ef93778c79e8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme",