 impose \u201cselective\u201d safeguard measures against Chinese imports until 2013. China was also made to agree to be treated as a non-market economy until 2016, which increases the possibility of higher anti-dumping duties being imposed on Chinese imports.18 16 See Ahmad (2005). 17 Authors\u2019 calculation based on data from Eurostat, COMTEXT. 18 This is particularly striking because on an average the anti-dumping duties on dumped imports from non- market economy tend to be more than 12 times higher than normal anti-dumping duties. Messerlin (2004, 42) reveals that in the anti-dumping investigations initiated by the US (between 1995 and 1998), which resulted in positive determination average dumping margin with price comparison as the basis for estimated normal One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 20 Using the first of the above mentioned provisions, US has initiated safeguard actions against selected Chinese imports and re-imposed quotas on a number of items. While the United States has re-imposed quota on seven items in May 2005 itself, EU also initiated action, which almost resulted in a major trade war. However, a last minute deal was struck with China on 10 June 2005 to limit 10 categories of Chinese T&C exports to the EU to between 8 and 12.5 percent growth above a specified base period until 2008. The EU eventually dropped its intention to impose import restrictions against Chinese textiles (Shrestha, 2005). To avoid frequent resort to safeguards measures, which had infused elements of uncertainty for US buyers as well as Chinese exporters, the United States Trade Representative (USTR) and Chinese Trade Minister reached a broad agreement on textile trade on 8 November 2005. The Agreement lasts through the life of the China WTO Textile Safeguard, i.e., 31 December 2008, covers 34 products and contains quotas that begin at low levels (USTR, 2005a; USTR 2005b). The Agreement, which went into effect on 1 January 2006, imposes tighter quota restriction on \u201ccore\u201d apparel products.19 Over the life of the Agreement, China can export 3.2 percent more of the covered products to the United States than if safeguards were invoked on all covered products for all three years. As a compromise, the United States promised to exercise \u201crestraint\u201d in future use of the safeguard on those products not covered by the Agreement. The Agreement also proposes smooth transition.20 This Agreement may have a destabilising effect for the Chinese T&C sector. However, marginal gains are likely to accrue to the preference-receiving countries of Africa and Central America and the Caribbean, as well as to India, the distant second in the T&C race and a potential target for other trade remedial actions. Those preference-receiving developing countries and LDCs, that are jubilant over the re-imposition of quota on Chinese products, should understand that such measures are likely to provide only temporary relief to them and that they themselves could face such measures, once they attain a critical mass. While countries like Argentina and Turkey also have imposed such measures against Chinese imports, Brazil has introduced a procedure for safeguard petitions aimed at \u201cstemming runaway growth of Chinese apparel and textile imports into the country.\u201d21 Criticising the reimposition of quota on Chinese garments because of its long-term implications, Ahmad (2005a) argues that this could set an extremely bad precedent: \u201cHistory tells us that quotas on one successful country today can mean quotas on the other next year, and on still others in the years hence.\u201d The tendency toward the use of trade remedy measures for protectionist purposes, if unchecked through clearly defined rules, can be expected to accelerate with serious implications, among others, for the trade in T&C products. The mandated review of anti- value of exports was only was 3.2 percent, whereas following non-mar