ing and subsidies rules as a part of the Doha Development Agenda (DDA) have not produced any result so far. The recently concluded Hong Kong Ministerial Conference of the WTO did not achieve a major breakthrough in terms of solving this problem, due in part to the focus of member delegations on other issues perceived to be of greater significance, such as the liberalisation of agriculture. As per part I of Annex D of the Ministerial", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4a5b1063-1564-481a-b0d7-4229c4e54e11": {"__data__": {"id_": "4a5b1063-1564-481a-b0d7-4229c4e54e11", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e2b0937fb881930f96abd4ee14a4ffaee9ed0d371ebda5299b39d9d308543c18"}}, "hash": "e2b0937fb881930f96abd4ee14a4ffaee9ed0d371ebda5299b39d9d308543c18", "text": "Declaration, which covers trade remedy measures, Ministers direct the Negotiating Group on Rules to intensify and accelerate the negotiating process in all areas of its mandate, on the basis of detailed textual proposals before the Group or yet to be submitted, and complete the process of analysing proposals by Participants on the Anti-dumping (AD) and Subsidies and Countervailing Measures (SCM) Agreements as soon as possible. They also mandate the Chairman to prepare, early enough to assure a timely outcome within the context of the 2006 end date for the Doha Development Agenda and taking account of progress in other areas of the negotiations, consolidated texts of the AD and SCM Agreements that shall be the basis for the final stage of the negotiations (emphasis in original). 22 Given the monumental task of completing negotiations on others areas by the end of the year and the absence of a strong constituency for the reform of trade remedy measures in general and anti-dumping in particular, there is every reason to believe that this issue may not receive the attention it deserves in days to come. Vertical Integration and Linkages Vertical integration signifies the existence of an integrated supply chain from the stage of cotton production, to yarn production, to fabric production, to the clothing industry, to transportation and other trade support facilities. In the context of T&C, existence of vertical integration tends to confer an advantage to the exporting firms. However, it also is necessary to understand that not all countries have the capacity and resources to integrate their supply chain vertically. For example, most West African countries, which grow cotton in abundance, do not have a strong textile industry. Countries like China, India, Thailand, Indonesia and Viet Nam have an integrated supply chain of textiles as well as clothing and are able to source a significant portion of raw materials from within the country. This helps them not only lower the costs of production due to reduced transportation costs of raw materials but also reduce the lead time. Reduction in lead time provides the twin advantages of being able to meet the delivery order, thereby enhancing credibility as a reliable source, and reducing the working capital requirement, which also means reduced bank interest for some. However, the existence of huge textile manufacturing capacity does not necessarily mean that the country also is competitive on exports of clothing products. For example, Pakistan\u2019s export profile suggests that 47.7 percent of its exports are textiles and made-up textile articles such as bed linens, while exports of clothing products are only 26.3 22 WTO (2005b), Paragraph 10 and 11 of Annex D. One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 22 percent. In the case of China, textile exports constitute 6.3 percent of total exports, whereas clothing accounts for much more, i.e., 11.9 percent (ILO, 2005a: 5). As the example of developing countries such as Hong Kong SAR, South Korea or Taiwan shows, the lack of domestic inputs does not necessarily translate into competitive disadvantages. In the early stage of the sector\u2019s development, these countries relied heavily on imports of raw materials and textiles (WTO, 2005a). IMF (2004) stresses that lack of domestic inputs in a sector like T&C need not always disadvantage the apparel trade, so long as inputs can be accessed at world prices with short lead times. In a market- dynamic sector such as T&C, a lesson from Pakistan and China is that states should allow garment exporters an undistorted choice between using local and imported fabrics. China, which produces both cotton and textiles, uses only 45 percent of domestic fabric for clothing exports (UNDP RCC, 2005b). As per recent figures, while the total exports of T&C products of China were US$61.12 billion in 2004, its import of fabrics and other raw materials was close to $20 billion (ILO, 2005a). Proximity Factor With the trend toward \u201clean retailing,\u201d producers that can provide quick turnaround time enjoy an important competitive advantage. Most studies argue that proximity to large markets [e.g., Mexico, Central America and the Caribbean countries to the US and Turkey, and Central and Eastern European Countries (CEEC) to the EU] is a key factor to ensure quick turnaround (WTO, 2005a: 5). Emphasizing the promptness in delivery as a key factor to remain afloat in the post-quota era, Abernathy and Weil (2004) argue that the proximity advantage will grow even greater as retailers raise the bar higher on the responsiveness and flexibility required of their suppliers. However, it is necessary to see whether if this is so even at a disaggregated level. For example,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2ab94c5a-51dc-4691-afd2-dcc9b0855241": {"__data__": {"id_": "2ab94c5a-51dc-4691-afd2-dcc9b0855241", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "de169e0189f4a276990671239c6fde65e0bde81f82e6ca60aaf83640e4798182"}, "3": {"node_id": "19eb5a25-f86f-46c2-9357-6e7259c1247d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3a364d06e22adb7c14f823fd9bc638ad3efcae8379c944e0b1e5b5ed6fb85d6d"}}, "hash": "aa46ebeba25fa03ea8b160d355c9ce39e738fcb012fe02c370c4c7aee92d58ac", "text": "in high-fashion products such as women\u2019s clothing, which does not require replenishment after one season, the issue of proximity may not matter. On the other hand, for replenishment products such as men\u2019s jeans, it would seem that producers closely located to the world\u2019s major markets are on solid footing (Abernathy, Volpe and Weil, 2004). There is no evidence to prove that proximity alone helps. For example, Mexico and Caribbean countries have been losing market share in the United States recently. Between 2001 and 2004, Mexico\u2019s apparel imports to the United States declined from 14.2 percent to 8.9 percent. This trend is continuing, with Mexico\u2019s exports of apparel to the United States declining by 5.9 percent in value terms and 8.7 percent in volume terms.23 Moreover, several East European countries in close proximity to European markets have been losing market share there. Comparing the T&C exports of five selected East European countries, it can be observed Romania\u2019s exports declined by 8.6 percent, Bulgaria\u2019s by 0.6 percent, Belarus\u2019 by 6.5 percent and Ukraine by 7.3 percent, while the 23 Authors\u2019 calculation based on data from USITC Interactive Tariff and Trade DataWeb. Flying Colours, Broken Threads 23 decline in Croatia exports were to the tune of 12.3 percent. The figure for Serbia and Montenegro is even more appalling at 46.3 percent.24 Turkey, another country relatively close to the European market, managed to increase its exports of clothing product to the EU in first nine months of the post-quota era by 4.1 percent in value terms and 3.2 percent in volume terms (Table A-4c). However, this performance also can be ascribed in part to the preferential market access in the EU market as well as to the enhanced competitiveness of the Turkish T&C sector. The above analysis points toward a rather limited role of proximity in shaping and influencing buyers\u2019 decision. It might continue to be important in a limited range of products, but overall significance is gradually reducing due to decreasing communications costs, shipping transit time, and improved efficiency of trade-related services, which tend to erode possible advantages. This is shown by the illustrious performance by the majority of the Asian countries in the post-quota era. Trade Agreements and Preferences Free trade agreements (FTAs), incorporated in the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) as a means to facilitate trade between geographically contiguous countries, now represent a complex maze of cross-continental agreements, often designed to suit the interests of sectoral lobbies, including T&C. FTAs are more liberal than the multilateral trading system espoused by the WTO. They involve deeper tariff cuts \u2013 sometimes reaching even close to zero. Since T&C products are one of the most heavily protected sectors in industrialised countries, with the average tariff as high as 32 percent on clothing, an FTA with a country like the United States make sense for developing countries eying America\u2019s ever-growing T&C market. Because benefits accorded to the FTA partner need not be accorded to any other WTO members,25 the incentive for developing countries to capture markets by excluding others from such benefits tends to be high. For example, most developing countries having FTAs with the United States increased the volume of their trade in T&C manifold in the past. For example, Mexico\u2019s T&C exports to the United States increased by more than 12-fold between 1990 and 2002. The example of Jordan is even more compelling: After signing an FTA with the United States in 2001, its exports rose to US$669 million in three years, an increase of 1,477 percent. Most Central American countries that signed the new United States-Dominican Republic Central American Free Trade Agreement (DR-CAFTA) in May 2004, are excited about the prospects of being able to gain preferential market access to the United States. This agreement received support even from the textile lobby, which wanted to contain the 24 \u201cTrade Issues\u201d European Commission http://tradeinfo.cec,eu.int/doclib/docs/2005/november/tradoc_126224.pdf 25 Though this system violates the fundamental principles of the WTO \u2013 \u201cmost favoured nations\u201d (MFN) treatment, as per provisions of Article XXIV of the GATT and/or Enabling Clause of the WTO, free trade agreements can deviate from this principle, subject to fulfilment of certain conditions.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "19eb5a25-f86f-46c2-9357-6e7259c1247d": {"__data__": {"id_": "19eb5a25-f86f-46c2-9357-6e7259c1247d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "de169e0189f4a276990671239c6fde65e0bde81f82e6ca60aaf83640e4798182"}, "2": {"node_id": "2ab94c5a-51dc-4691-afd2-dcc9b0855241", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "aa46ebeba25fa03ea8b160d355c9ce39e738fcb012fe02c370c4c7aee92d58ac"}}, "hash": "3a364d06e22adb7c14f823fd9bc638ad3efcae8379c944e0b1e5b5ed6fb85d6d", "text": "One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 24 growing influence of China in the US T&C market. Similarly, several Eastern European countries that had entered into association agreements with the EU before for