d quota-free market access provided by the EU to all LDCs under \u201cEverything but Arms\u201d (EBA) initiative; b) preferential market access provided by the EU to African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) countries under Cotonou Agreement; c) preference provided to the African countries by the United States under AGOA; and d) preferential access provided by the United States, Caribbean Basin Trade Partnership Agreement (CBPTA) to Caribbean countries; and e) Canadian GSP. Out of these preferential arrangements, only two \u2013 EU\u2019s EBA initiative and Canada\u2019s preferential trading arrangements - are generalised in the sense that they confer advantages to all LDCs.26 Although the United States also provides GSP for LDCs, the same does not include T&C products. For all practical purpose, therefore, T&C products originating from Asian LDCs do not enjoy any preferential access to the US market. While the examples of Jordan and Mexico and several African countries and Caribbean countries are worth highlighting, it is necessary to understand that they benefited in part because of the quota restriction imposed on highly competitive Asian countries. With the end of quotas, Mexico is now exposed to direct competition with China and continues to lose market share in the US market. The share of Mexico and CBI and that of AGOA countries in the US T&C imports declined as discussed earlier (Table A-1a). Some AGOA-eligible countries developed garment export industries that did not exist before AGOA\u2019s enactment in 2000. Asian companies opened up textile and clothing factories in sub-Saharan Africa by aiming at expansion of exports to the US market under AGOA. However, many investors, including Asian, fled Sub-Saharan Africa countries with the end of MFA. For example, six of Lesotho\u2019s 50 clothes factories shut down in Lesotho in December 2004, leaving 6,650 workers jobless overnight, without being informed or paid. Owners of those factories were from Taiwan, China, Malaysia and Mauritius.27 In Namibia, the Malaysian-owned garment factory shut down in April 2005 (Rolfe and Woodward, 2005). In Swaziland, nearly 75 percent of textile factories say they have no firm orders since March 2005 (Wines, 2005). One disadvantage that these countries face is their pegged currency exchange rate to South Africa\u2019s rand. Since 2002, the rand has appreciated against the US dollar, driven by a boom in commodities like gold; this makes countries\u2019 exports more expensive. However, other obstacles for exports that AGOA member nations face are concentration on low 26 Canadian GSP for the LDCs does not accord duty-free treatment to Myanmar. 27 BBC News Online, 12 January 2005. http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/4169587.stm Flying Colours, Broken Threads 25 value-added production, lack of local supply linkages, high transport costs, erratic and expensive electricity, poor infrastructure and relatively low worker productivity (Rolfe and Woodward, 2005). These are common issues among Asian countries as well. Since the United States re-imposed quotas on Chinese T&C imports, exports from AGOA countries, as well as other countries having preferential access to the US market, may revive. AGOA countries need to build stronger local supply linkages because garment makers must make or buy their fabrics in sub-Saharan African countries, if not purchasing them from the United States, to continue enjoying duty-free access to the United States after September 2007. Other examples of countries with preferential access that are not doing well can be found in Asia itself. Four Asian LDCs, namely, Bangladesh, Cambodia, Lao PDR and Nepal, are losing their market share in the EU despite EBA. For example, EU imports of T&C products from Bangladesh declined by 8.5 in value terms and 13.8 percent in volume this year (Table A-4a). Similarly, Cambodia\u2019s exports to the EU market declined by 13.5 percent in value and 8.2 percent in volume terms (Table A-4b). The figures for Lao PDR were also similar, with 7.2 percent decline in value terms and 7.1 percent decline in volume terms (Table A-4f).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "60f5b6d1-0c5e-4188-9a60-4d20f40e0ec0": {"__data__": {"id_": "60f5b6d1-0c5e-4188-9a60-4d20f40e0ec0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4d5a43b0de8efb51c184fbdd151b6e85d4f6faafc05792584f80db8f6ac9b223"}, "2": {"node_id": "d928c6cc-1187-438b-80ad-5355713e024c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "72fe65afbbadf5d5e82421470afacb53265b5a2dc09d32937d5fa78615fbf35d"}}, "hash": "66526a2c0c8f47a56b9b21d15ff14eaa5373265dff438164c4b75b6202cf6fd3", "text": "Nepal\u2019s performance has been even more depressing, as the decline in T&C exports to the EU market were 9.8 percent in value and 14.2 percent in volume (Table A-4g). What are the reasons for the precipitous declines in these LDC exports of T&C products to the EU, despite the preferential arrangement? The first reason is the phasing out of quotas and increased competition leading to downward pressures on prices, which exporters from LDCs were not able to accept. The second reason, more subtle, is the issue of rules of origin (ROO), which is designed to protect the interest of the RMG lobby", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "20d416ee-7cc1-45f1-849a-8bf2f1b16623": {"__data__": {"id_": "20d416ee-7cc1-45f1-849a-8bf2f1b16623", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "14087472f4fa54af0d4f35f9b5487e6a8836ad28c673a444e69a02140b4f29b6"}, "3": {"node_id": "3a827460-d330-4622-a426-bce85663e1bc", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "87794fec909a4d35a9b431c577a4e53ac50f193969da9126aef2a9831fa1a8f2"}}, "hash": "8687755fef0015d63dfa1433138fb24c8f75e672d00c872617a0345d0a2f9d14", "text": "within the EU (See Box 1). The seemingly liberal attitude adopted by the EU under the EBA initiative should be seen in the context of a protectionist undercurrent that remains prevalent within the European economy. One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 26 Box 1: Enduring Enigma of Rules of Origin Started with the objective of preventing trade deflection and promoting the creation of a vertically integrated sector in beneficiary countries, Rules of Origin (ROO) has become a protectionist tool in the hands of the donor countries to prevent imports. Developed countries provide preferential access with one hand, but at the same time they impose rigid ROO requirements and take away the benefits. ROO may distort the choices of producers from beneficiary countries, leading them to use inputs of less efficient producers or constraining their methods of production through technical requirements, or both. Beyond administrative costs, producers who wish to satisfy ROO thus may incur the cost of using a sub-optimal mix of inputs. Further, there is no evidence to suggest to that ROO has helped beneficiary countries in creating vertical integration (WTO, 2005a: 55). The major fallout of ROO is that this requirement is very cumbersome, inefficient and resource- demanding. It is costly and complex to administer. For example, the administrative costs of certifying origin in European Free Trade Area (EFTA) range from 3 percent to 5 percent value of export transactions.28 Similarly, the administrative costs of providing the documentary evidence to support the certificate of origin under the North American Free Trade Area (NAFTA) are in the region of 1.8 percent of the value of exports. The distorted impact of the rules, resulting from the need to use local and higher-cost inputs to qualify, may be equivalent to an average duty of around 4.3 percent (World Bank, 2004). The world is not without options, provided there is a willingness on the part of the GSP donor countries to modify their ROO requirements. Some useful initiatives are already in place. Two examples of flexible ROO are: a) a lower-value-added requirement, say 25 percent; and b) allowing for single-stage transformation. Another way to maintain the rigid ROO, but allow for cumulation, i.e., treating inputs derived from a very large number of countries as originating in the exporting country. Canada has taken the lead on this matter. For example, in the case of T&C, the Canadian scheme allows cumulation amongst all developing countries, including most efficient producers like China and India, with a 25 percent value-added requirement (Adhikari, 2005). Increase in exports of LDCs in the aftermath of the reform is a testament to the fact that ROO reform could be a powerful instrument to enhance exports from LDCs.29 The ROO under the EBA is probably the most onerous, which requires that at least two finishing operations - a double transformation - occur in the exporting country to qualify for duty free-access. Since LDCs do not have an industrial base to produce textiles and have to rely on imported raw materials, they are not likely to qualify. This, in part, explains the reason why the preference utilisation rate for EBA (as measured against simple average tariff lines) was merely 37.8 percent in 2003, and the country-specific clothing preferences of the Asian LDCs in 2004 were: 33.8 percent for Bangladesh; 30.9 percent for Cambodia; and 65.8 percent for Nepal (WTO, 2005a: 51, 53). One way to ease the burden on LDC exporters is a process called \u201cregional cumulation,\u201d i.e., allowing countries within a regional trading arrangement to use raw materials from 28 Inter-American Development Bank (IADB) report cited in Adhikari (2005). 29 For example, Bangladesh\u2019s exports to Canada surged by 3.3 time and those of Cambodia increased by 7.1 times. Export value index for Bangladesh showed a jump from 112.5 in 2002 to 370.8 in two-year period ending 2004. Figures for Cambodia are even more impressive \u2013 it went up from 348.7 in 2002 to 2,469.7 in 2004. See WTO (2005a): 69. Flying Colours, Broken Threads 27 other countries within the arrangement. EU has provided such facilities to Cambodia and Lao PDR within the Association of South East Asian Nations (ASEAN) and to Bangladesh, Bhutan, Maldives and Nepal within the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3a827460-d330-4622-a426-bce85663e1bc": {"__data__": {"id_": "3a827460-d330-4622-a426-bce85663e1bc", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "14087472f4fa54af0d4f35f9b5487e6a8836ad28c673a444e69a02140b4f29b6"}, "2": {"node_id": "20d416ee-7cc1-45f1-849a-8bf2f1b16623", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8687755fef0015d63dfa1433138fb24c8f75e672d00c872617a0345d0a2f9d14"}}, "hash": "87794fec909a4d35a9b431c577a4e53ac50f193969da9126aef2a9831fa1a8f2", "text": "This provision, for example, allows clothing producer from Nepal to use fabrics from India and Lao producers to use fabrics from Thailand (provided that required transformation has been done in India and Thailand respectively) \u2013 and still qualify for duty-free access under EBA. This provides for slightly more freedom in sourcing decisions than is available under", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metad