ugh SAARC countries have requested the European Union to extend SAARC cumulation to \u201cSAARC-plus-ASEAN-super- cumulation\u201d this request is still under discussion. Therefore, it is premature to make any informed analysis on the basis of a possible breakthrough on this issue Duty-free, Quota-free Market Access While discussing duty-free, quota-free market access for LDCs, it is necessary to look at two distinct but interrelated issues. First is the issue of predictability of market access. Numerous conditions attached to preferential market access provided to LDCs \u2013 graduation clauses such as ceiling and caps, finite duration, and other conditions, sometimes going beyond trade-related issues \u2013 results in uncertainty of access. Since most schemes are unilateral and voluntary, they can be withdrawn by donor countries at will. Uncertainty regarding the conditions of access to major markets could represent a serious obstacle to potential investors in T&C sectors in the LDCs (WTO, 2005a: 69). The second issue relates to the discriminatory treatment provided by the two major economies to two groups of LDCs as mentioned above. Asian LDCs do not enjoy preferential access in the US market at all, while access to the EU market is subject to stringent ROO requirements. Asian LDCs, therefore, face double jeopardy \u2013 of not being able to compete with giant neighbours like China, India, Indonesia and Pakistan on equal terms (i.e., by paying MFN tariffs), as well as not being able to compete with other LDCs, which receive preferences from both the United States and EU under extremely favourable terms. Consequently, exports of Asian LDCs continue to face high tariffs in the US market. Cambodia paid US$152 million in import duties to the United States in 2002, compared the duties paid by Norway of US$24 million for exports five times higher (UNDP RCC, 30 For certain textile and clothing products, but subject to quantitative limits, Cambodia, Laos and Nepal have requested and been granted a derogation from the rules for certain textiles and clothing products such that originating inputs from any countries belonging to the SAARC, ASEAN or the ACP can count as originating materials. See Brenton (2003). One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 28 2005b). In recent years, Bangladesh has paid over more than US$300 million in US duties, compared to duties paid by France of US$330 million for exports 13 times higher (Rahman, 2005). These are highly regressive transfers that outstrip the bilateral foreign aid these poor countries receive (UNDP RCC, 2005b). The situation on the ground is desperate, calling for desperate measures. RMG entrepreneurs in Nepal, interviewed by the authors during a field visit in October 2005, informed that those who have not closed their factories were hopeful about survival if they are provided duty-free access to the US market, and they were waiting for the same. If such facilities are not granted, they will close their factories because they cannot afford to hold on to their premises by continuing to incur the minimum fixed overheads. During a field visit to Lao PDR conducted by the authors in November 2005, most stakeholders demanded duty-free and quota-free market access from the industrialised countries so as to enable their garment industry to survive in the face of increased competition. Stakeholders contacted in Bangladesh and Cambodia during the field visits were equally vocal about the need to provide fair and equitable treatment to Asian LDCs. The only way to solve the problems mentioned above is not only to provide duty-free, quota- free market access to all LDCs, covering all their products, but also to make it binding them at the WTO to reduce uncertainty and ensure predictability of market access. However, this has indeed been a long-drawn-out, often highly frustrating, battle that LDCs have been fighting since 1992 without much success (See Box 2).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5de5288d-f35b-4495-814c-a71e38fbb799": {"__data__": {"id_": "5de5288d-f35b-4495-814c-a71e38fbb799", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "79d390ee9a8e8227411c923c877540bcb5c0046fc539c8294fadb638dd732331"}, "2": {"node_id": "74018cbd-e5b0-48d5-8dd5-d09aa6d3a1da", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "efeb067ca9d42258055bce995ea7ff38daa5d4646245c7b6d17ddd5702931af4"}}, "hash": "87820320b71bdb06b984fde158153def7fdd38eb98985884327126bdfee4744c", "text": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads 29 Box 2: LDCs\u2019 Battle for Duty-free and Quota-free Market Access In 1992, at UNCTAD VIII, the Cartagena Commitment urged that exports from LDCs be guaranteed duty-free access to major markets, but the idea was stillborn", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fbcd1949-76fd-4566-9239-805877e374c5": {"__data__": {"id_": "fbcd1949-76fd-4566-9239-805877e374c5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "720f783b7c58eba254307110e7d119fc39af174c6043a6b1a88520cbb2eea5a1"}, "3": {"node_id": "264f1b4b-1c90-40ce-b0c5-6ed9e8e8f6a2", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d78da3ee893caf540ab8069c94e2450bf117d286a17ce43c64227ab6e30c29f5"}}, "hash": "e4055161498f081c24fb392a02fda09fba13a6bd5b7cffdf48f136feb6c7eb7d", "text": "(Ricupero, 1999). The idea was reintroduced in the Singapore Ministerial Meeting of the WTO in December 1996, when the then-Director-General of WTO made a plea to the members to consider the proposal seriously; nonetheless, there was lukewarm response to his proposal. Finally, a Ministerial Declaration came out with a non-committal language. During preparation for the Third WTO Ministerial Conference in Seattle held in November- December 1999, the EU formally launched a proposal directed at \u201centering into a commitment to ensure duty-free market access not later than at the end of the new round of negotiations for essentially all products exported by the LDCs.\u201d Following the failure of the Seattle Ministerial Conference, the proposal for granting duty-free and/or quota-free access for \u201cessentially all\u201d products was discussed in the context of various international fora and included in the UNCTAD X Bangkok Plan of Action (Inama, 2002: 85). This issue received further impetus during the Millennium Summit held in September 2000, which adopted the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs). Goal 8 of the MDGs makes \u201caddressing the special needs of the LDCs, includes tariff- and quota-free access for LDC exports,\u201d as one of the targets to be achieved by 2015. Two months before the Third UN Conference of Least Developed Countries (UNLDC-III) Conference, the EU launched its \u201cEverything But Arms\u201d (EBA) initiative. Following this, the need to provide duty- free, quota-free market access to LDCs was clearly highlighted in the Brussels Plan of Action, adopted by UNDLC\u2013III in May 2001. When the Doha Development Agenda (DDA) was adopted in November 2001 by the Fourth WTO Ministerial Conference, Ministers committed themselves to the objective of duty-free, quota-free market access for products originating from LDCs (Paragraph 42 of DDA). Even after several years of negotiations, the issue has not resolved in a way that is going to be beneficial to the LDCs. Due to much-touted promises for \u201cearly harvest\u201d on DDA for the LDCs, a major breakthrough during the Sixth WTO Ministerial Conference of the WTO in Hong Kong in December 2005 was anticipated. However, diluting the spirit of earlier discussions, including the one undertaken at the Special Session of Committee on Trade and Development, the Hong Kong Ministerial Declaration allows developed countries to permit duty free quota free access for LDC products to only 97 percent of their tariff lines.31 This is a major setback to the T&C sector of Asian LDCs because the major items that would fall outside the \u201ccovered list\u201d will be precisely these items. According to Ahmad (2005b), an ardent critique of EU/US trade policy on T&C, these countries keep tariff on T&C products high, provide preferential market access to select countries, require preference-receiving countries to purchase inputs from their countries in order to qualify for the rules of origin requirements, thereby creating a captive market 31 Although the declaration starts on a positive note stating that developed countries shall and developing countries should \u201cProvide duty-free and quota-free market access on a lasting basis, for all products originating from all LDCs by 2008 or no later than the start of the implementation period in a manner that ensures stability, security and predictability\u201d [Paragraph 36 (a) i ]. However, as per the next Paragraph \u201cMembers facing difficulties at this time to provide market access as set out above shall provide duty-free and quota-free market access for at least 97 per cent of products originating from LDCs \u2026\u201d [Paragraph 36 (a) ii]. See WTO (2005b), Annex F. One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 30 for their upstream industries (yarn, fabrics and accessories).32 All this is done at the insistence of their respective T&C lobbies, which are very powerful. For example, the US T&C lobby led by National Council of Textiles Associations (NCTO) was actively engaged in thwarting the LDC proposal. Its major fear has been that countries like Bangladesh and Cambodia, which are competitive in T&C products could flood the US market with their products if zero tariff access is provided to them. The NCTO immediately opposed the idea of extending duty free treatment to Asian LDCs, particularly because the latter can use the raw materials from the most competitive sources like China.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "264f1b4b-1c90-40ce-b0c5-6ed9e8e8f6a2": {"__data__": {"id_": "264f1b4b-1c90-40ce-b0c5-6ed9e8e8f6a2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "720f783b7c58eba254307110e7d119fc39af174c6043a6b1a88520cbb2eea5a1"}, "2": {"node_id": "fbcd1949-76fd-4566-9239-805877e374c5", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e4055161498f081c24fb392a02fda09fba13a6bd5b7cffdf48f136feb6c7eb7d"}}, "hash": "d78da3ee893caf540ab8069c94e2450bf117d286a17ce43c64227ab6e30c29f5", "text": "This is where a second line of reasoning appears, which is if these facilities are provided within the WTO framework, it would not be possible for the United States to dictate the rules of origin and compel them to use US fabrics. Producers from preference receiving countries could even source fabrics from China, which is, as NCTO would argue, against the interest of US jobs. Praising the Hong Kong outcome,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7d048230-ed4e-4fd7-8f27-6c4808810def": {"__data__": {"id_": "7d048230-ed4e-4fd7-8f27-6c4808810def", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Developme