essing because of disagreement over which formula for the reduction of tariffs should be used. At Hong Kong ministers could only manage to adopt a formula35 with coefficients at levels which shall inter alia: reduce or eliminate tariffs, including the reduction or elimination of tariff peaks, high tariffs and tariff escalation, especially on products of export interest to developing countries. The Ministerial Declaration also states the intention to take fully into account the special needs and interests of developing countries, including through 32 See Ahmad, Munir (2005b) for further details. 33 NTCO Press Release available at http://www.ncto.org/newsroom/yr2005.pdf 34 Ibid. 35 Ministers agreed to Swiss Formula, which is known to reduce higher tariffs more steeply than the lower ones. This modality of tariff reduction was applied during the Tokyo Round of multilateral trade negotiations under the GATT. See Market Access: Negotiations; A simple guide \u2013 NAMA Negotiations available at http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/markacc_e/nama_negotiations_e.htm Flying Colours, Broken Threads 31 less than full reciprocity in reduction commitment. The ministers instructed the Negotiating Group to finalise its structure and details \u201cas soon as possible\u201d.36 Some countries have proposed to include the negotiations on T&C on a \u201csectoral mode,\u201d which implies countries are expected to make a reciprocal offer of zero-to-zero tariff reduction. While sectoral liberalisation is not likely to occur before the core modalities are finalised, developing countries are not likely to agree to the idea of initiating tariffs negotiations under this mode. This is because of the fear that their T&C industry, which too is highly protected, also could be threatened by cheap imports from more competitive countries like China. Bound tariffs on T&C products are very high in emerging economies like India, Malaysia and Pakistan, and most of them have bound their tariffs sparingly. For example, as per the Schedules of Concessions submitted to the WTO,37 India has bound tariffs on only 216 items under the list covered by the Agreement on Textile and Clothing (ATC); the simple average of these tariffs is 38.6 percent. Malaysia\u2019s schedule of concession does not reflect any binding on T&C tariff lines, which means that it can raise the tariff to even astronomical levels if circumstances so dictate. Similarly, Pakistan\u2019s schedule of commitment shows that simple average bound rates on T&C tariff lines is 43.8 percent. In parallel, however, textile lobbies are calling for separate talks, referred to as the \u201cSpecial Textile Sectoral,\u201d which is different than the normal sectoral mentioned above. Separate talks are believed to be the best way forward to discussing textile tariffs, by coalitions such as Euratex and Global Alliance for Fair Textile Trade, a worldwide coalition of more than 90 exporting textile and apparel companies. They propose that all countries reduce, harmonise and bind their customs duties on textile and apparel at a maximum of 15 percent for finished products.38 Two schools of thoughts are emerging on the issue of preference erosion. The preference- receiving countries, particularly LDCs, feel that they will be put under tremendous competitive pressure if steep cuts are made on T&C MFN tariffs. As noted above when the preference margin is reduced or eliminated, they will not be able to hold on with more competitive countries like China and India. Therefore, they are demanding that some form of adjustment assistance should be provided to overcome these challenges.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "30bf4f4b-53e8-497a-a162-203a7309023e": {"__data__": {"id_": "30bf4f4b-53e8-497a-a162-203a7309023e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a31eb186f84654e52b6f6bccff6891db604fc648a7c71a3cacb0b2f2e02734ea"}, "2": {"node_id": "7d048230-ed4e-4fd7-8f27-6c4808810def", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "134376c9e4f070a0cc76771835f332fb9804958e824d2bcd1008168daa2343fb"}}, "hash": "998337a76d469eeebe56770a00d461efc9df7e04bf7a6bebaef7e636342aa5ab", "text": "Therefore, they are demanding that some form of adjustment assistance should be provided to overcome these challenges. Another school of thought views preference itself as an impediment to the creation of a competitive atmosphere in the preference-receiving countries, with the corollary that preferences have not really served their purpose. Those who subscribe to this view also argue that conditionality imposed by the donor countries \u2013 including ROO \u2013 lead to limited utilisation of preferences anyway. Since, as the argument goes, there is very limited preference", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "50cac861-04c3-4f69-bc0d-0407f01cd23a": {"__data__": {"id_": "50cac861-04c3-4f69-bc0d-0407f01cd23a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0f2041969be52667acc6e26b95f150ab72f924e49c8364d0d30649e952d4457b"}, "3": {"node_id": "2153a8f3-05d3-419c-badc-2f486f830ad1", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fb42dc4329a0022d4417993ebdccf3b70895092f1146aca63c6fdb0595d956ae"}}, "hash": "5fb8ca747614c9e0549d5361344d9401be7ce391f07e2f748d2bfa6b17eb9d40", "text": "margin at the first place, preference-receiving countries need not really worry about losing the same. Some of these issues have been discussed in detail in a recent study (Low, Piermartini and Richtering, 2005), according to which many LDCs would, suffer little or no preference erosion because their export structure is such that they enjoy MFN duty-free treatment on 36 See WTO (2005b), Paragraph 14. 37 Downloadable from http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/schedules_e/goods_schedules_e.htm 38 EmergingTextiles.com (2005c), http://www.emergingtextiles.com/?q=art&s=051123Atrad&r=free, One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 32 a large share of exports to five major markets (Australia, Canada, EU15, Japan and United States). However, the report also points out clearly that textile and clothing are the two major sectors in which preference erosions are likely to be more severe. IV. Case Studies In the long run, competitiveness is the most critical factor that will determine the success of any country. This is because buyers constantly look to find the cheapest source of supply - and with competitive pressure intensifying, it is only fair to expect them to behave the way they do. This also explains, in part, the reason why there are waves of adjustment taking place even in highly competitive countries. For example, Pakistan invested heavily on the modernisation of its textile mills in order to enhance its competitiveness in textile production. The import of capital equipment (textile machinery) during the past four years is testimony to its attempt toward the modernising the industry (see Table 2). Table 2: Import of Textile Machinery in Pakistan Year Million US$ Percentage change 1999-2000 210.9 28.6 2000-01 370.2 75.5 2001-02 406.9 9.9 2002-03 531.9 30.7 2003-04 (July-April) 455.0 - Source: Government of Pakistan, cited in Din (2005):77 Pakistan also has formulated a long-term development strategy to \u201cfacilitate the transformation of the textile sector into a strong, dynamic and internationally competitive industry led by the private sector (Din, 2005).\u201d Similarly, Governments of Bangladesh, Philippines and India have relaxed or are in the process of relaxing their labour laws to face competitive challenges. Other countries are planning to develop EPZs and make changes in the regulatory environment in order to facilitate exports. Others have planned ahead, anticipating the challenges, to diversify their markets, invested on image building or started focusing on niche products and achieved success. Of the various strategies adopted so far, three such strategies, which have become successful in countries where they have been applied, are presented below in the form of case studies. Improved Labour Standard \u2013 A Case of Cambodia Cambodia\u2019s access to the US market from 1999 to 2004 was contingent on its record of compliance with labour standards, with the quota rates increased every year based on successful compliance. In order to satisfy this requirement, Cambodia adopted a corporate social responsibility programme in collaboration with the International Labour Organisation (ILO), known as Better Factories Cambodia (formerly known as the ILO Garment Sector Project). Begun in 2001 to help Cambodia\u2019s garment sector achieve and maintain improvements in working conditions, the project monitors and reports on working conditions in Cambodian garment factories according to national and Flying Colours, Broken Threads 33 international standards, helps factories to improve their productivity, and works with the Government and international buyers to ensure a rigorous and transparent cycle of improvement. The main objective of the programme is to help Cambodian garment factories constantly improve the conditions of labour by strictly adhering to national labour legislation as well as international conventions Cambodia has signed as a member of the ILO. The project follows a targeted programme of setting minimum standards as agreed by the decision of a tripartite (Government, private sector and trade union), monitoring compliance and providing advisory support and capacity building training to stakeholders to help compliance (ILO 2005a, ILO 2005b). Box 3: Better Factories Cambodia and the Other Side of the Coin The latest report of Better Factories Cambodia, covering 34 garment factories, has noted significant improvement in labour conditions in the garment factories. The report found no evidence of forced or child labour \u2013 based on age-verifying documents. Only four registered factories disallowed the freedom to unionise, and the majority of factories comply with the national minimum-wage and overtime requirements.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2153a8f3-05d3-419c-badc-2f486f830ad1": {"__data__": {"id_": "2153a8f3-05d3-419c-badc-2f486f830ad1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0f2041969be52667acc6e26b95f150ab72f924e49c8364d0d30649e952d4457b"}, "2": {"node_id": "50cac861-04c3-4f69-bc0d-0407f01cd23a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5fb8ca747614c9e0549d5361344d9401be7ce391f07e2f748d2bfa6b17eb9d40"}}, "hash": "fb42dc4329a0022d4417993ebdccf3b70895092f1146aca63c6fdb0595d956ae", "text": "According to this report, all monitored factories grant 18 days of paid annual leave, 63 percent provide maternity leave but with half pay, and 71 percent ensure that overtime occurs voluntarily (ILO, 2005b). This report provides a glimpse into the Cambodian garment industry, but data are still unclear on the number of home workers and other informal employees. Moreover, study conducted by Sim (2004) shows that health conditions of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e6918f93-20fd-482d-8a95-16fc2e02f899": {"__data__": {"id_": "e6918f93-20fd-482d-8a95-16fc2e02f899", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "de258369b4ea13cd6dafa8003646d7e351378eaa56a10ae456e6a49f4618661f"}}, "hash": "de258369b4ea13cd6dafa8003646d7e351378eaa56a10ae456e6a49f4618661f", "text": "the workers have deteriorated due to working conditions such as long working hours, noisy environment, high temperatures, and excessive use of chemicals. While the 1997 Cambodian Labour Code stipulates that all garment factories are required to have health care facilities on the premises or access to primary health care for their workers, most often it is workers\u2019 responsibility. Workers must pay for treatment out of their wages; therefore most prefer to avoid formal health care. About 40 percent of workers surveyed said that their health expenses are as expensive as housing costs (Sim, 2004: 43-46). Because the information under this project is made public on the ILO website, with the consent of the factories monitored, it provides an independent source of information for retailers. Buyers seem to have made use of such information while making sourcing decisions. As per a buyers\u2019 survey conducted by the Foreign Investment Advisory Services (2004) of the World Bank Group, more than 60 per cent of buyers interviewed said compliance with labour standards was of equal or more importance compared to considerations of price, quality and lead times. The survey also found that Cambodia\u2019s labour standards were seen as higher than other Asian countries (Bangladesh, China, Thailand and Viet Nam). It also was revealed that 60 percent of the buyers planned to increase their garment purchases from Cambodia, while none said they would cut back. As per the information provided by the ILO, during the first quarter of 2005 Cambodia was not only able to increase the share of its exports to the US market in seasonally adjusted terms, but also was able to maintain levels of employment in the sector while factories consolidated. For example, the percentage of factories with more than 5,000 workers has increased from 3 percent in 2004 to 7.3 percent in 2005 (ILO, 2005a: 36, 39). The US import figures for the first nine months of 2005 confirm that Cambodia\u2019s exports to the United States have increased by 17.4 percent in value terms and 17.1 percent in One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 34 volume terms (Table A-4b). The strategy that worked in the US market does not seem to have worked in the EU however; such a trend is not visible in the EU market. Since Cambodia\u2019s export to the US market is 3.2 times higher than its exports to the EU, increased US exports should be seen as an indicator of the buyers\u2019 appreciation of efforts to improve labour standards. This is a model worth replicating in other countries, particularly the LDCs, which face severe competitive disadvantages due to their inherent weaknesses on several fronts. However, it is necessary to take the private sector \u2013 garment manufacturers and/or exporters \u2013 into confidence before initiating such a programme, because it is likely to view any programme that could affect the bottom line with suspicion. It may be easier to convince the private sector by arguing that almost all EU and US buyers want to ensure that their suppliers strictly adhere to core labour standards. Despite all this, Governments and international community including ILO and civil society have not been able to replicate Cambodian models in other developing countries and LDCs so far. One argument that is often advanced by the skeptics concerns the futility of replicating the model in other LDCs, because, as the argument goes, if all the LDCs have similar labour standards, the same may not remain an important factor influencing buyers\u2019 decision. However, from a human development perspective, this should be considered a welcome development. While a \u201crace to the bottom\u201d operationalises the fallacy of composition, a \u201crace to the top\u201d among poor countries to improve their labour standards concomitantly has the potential to overcome this fallacy, because it enlarges their own markets. The experience of Sri Lanka, which is not an LDC, has not been very encouraging, though. Based on considerable improvement in labour standards and its record of compliance with eight Core Labour Conventions of the ILO, Sri Lanka made a formal request to the EU seeking additional GSP benefits under the \u201clabour clause\u201d of EU GSP. After an independent evaluation, EU granted the incentives under the clause with effect from 1 February 2004. This allows Sri Lankan 40 to 60 percent reductions in normal GSP tariffs. However, whatever limited evidence is available suggests that Sri Lanka has not been able to increase its exports to the EU market despite such preferences39. Table A-4j shows that Sri Lanka\u2019s exports to the EU declined by 6.2 percent in value terms and 3.1 percent in volume", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9e750f53-c230-4bfa-9ba0-58894b764738": {"__data__": {"id_": "9e750f53-c230-4bfa-9ba0-58894b764738", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia