actories in Sri Lanka. This sector contributed to 62.3 percent of total industrial export earnings and 48.8 percent of total exports in 2004. In terms of markets, Sri Lankan T&C products are destined to the US market and 37 percent to the EU. During the first half of the current decade, T&C sector emerged from a short period of negative export growth to positive growth in 2003 (Kelegama and Weeraratne, 2005). Since the Sri Lankan T&C sector is not considered highly competitive due to several factors - higher wages, low productivity of workers, high cost of utilities and lack of backward linkages - private entrepreneurs realised they should focus on niche products in order to create an opportunity for themselves. Taking advantage of the relatively high level of education of the workers,40 coupled with fast learning aptitude, Sri Lanka started focusing on a distinct segment of apparel, i.e., women\u2019s undergarments. As per the available data, Sri Lankan exports of three product categories (women's or girls' cotton briefs and panties, women's or girls' panties of man- made fibres and brassieres of all types) have achieved healthy growth. These categories saw growth in both the EU and US market in 2004, but in the first nine months of 2005 there has been a dramatic surge of exports (909.9 percent) in the US market, particularly in the first category, and healthy growth in other two categories. Exceptional growth of exports of cotton panties was not only observed in value terms, but also in volume terms, where it grew by 685 percent. However, exports to the EU declined by 22.9 percent and 18.3 percent respectively in the first two categories. Nonetheless, due to 18.8 percent growth achieved on brassieres\u2019 exports, the overall exports of these niche products declined by only 1.2 percent in the EU market. Table 3: Sri Lankan Exports of Women\u2019s Undergarments HS Product description 2003 2004 % Jan-Sep 2004 Jan-Sep 2005 % Imports into the US market (figures in 1,