 \u2013 which may include South Asian and African countries. Second, it has become a supplier of fabrics to all other ASEAN countries, as seen by the profile of its fabric exports. Except for Singapore and Brunei, which do not have strong T&C sectors, all other member countries of ASEAN have increased their imports from Thailand. The EU\u2019s policy of allowing for ASEAN cumulation to achieve ROO requirements under the EBA seems also to have indirectly helped Thailand. Since its immediate LDC neighbours such as Lao PDR and Cambodia do not have well-developed textile and other accessories manufacturing set up, the EU\u2019s requirement to use fabrics from ASEAN to qualify for ROO requirements provides a captive market for Thai textiles. Likewise, export diversification in the case of garments is quite impressive, and there are lessons to be learned for other Asian developing countries. While it might be possible for other ASEAN developing countries like Indonesia and Viet Nam to follow the same trajectory, LDCs like Cambodia and Lao PDR probably will have to wait for several years to make this happen. Due to relatively a liberalised and hassle- free preferential trade regime within ASEAN, increasing intra-regional trade to make up for losses in multilateral trade seems feasible, but in the SAARC region that is not possible because regional trade liberalisation efforts are yet to take concrete shape (UNDP RCC, 2005c). However, having India and Pakistan as cotton fibres and textiles supplies may help other South Asian countries\u2019 exports of cotton garment products to the EU under EBA. Flying Colours, Broken Threads 37 If regional trade is not possible for the South Asian countries, what is the potential for South-South trade for them? Or what is the potential for South-South trade in general, if at all? As mentioned above, the tariffs rates on T&C in developing countries are much higher than prevailing rates in industrialised countries. However, developing countries do not want to reduce their tariff barriers to all countries due to the fear of de- industrialisation and consequent job losses. Worse still, a climate of mutual suspicion tends to cloud the prospects for South-South trade, even among the highly competitive players. Besides protecting the industry, the textile sector is protected for one more reason, i.e., to ensure vertical integration in the country. This not only helps developing countries meet the stringent ROO of preferential trading arrangements, but also helps them strengthen backward linkage of the clothing sector with the rest of the economy. These are the very factors responsible for the slow progress under Generalised System of Trade Preferences (GSTP), established on 19 April 1989 under the auspices of the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) with the objective of promoting South-South trade. So far, 44 countries have become members of this Agreement, out of which only 24 countries have exchanged tariff concessions. However, of late developing countries have exhibited a renewed sense of urgency to enhance South-South trade cooperation, which is indeed a positive sign. The Sao Paulo Consensus, which was agreed to during the Eleventh Session on UNCTAD has provided impetus to this process. The Consensus emphasises that UNCTAD should also continue its support for the revitalisation and greater utilisation of the GSTP among Developing Countries and other initiatives that stimulate South-South trade (UNCTAD, 2004a: Paragraph 97).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c5dcefd1-bb8d-411f-891e-55fe7ea8f8c6": {"__data__": {"id_": "c5dcefd1-bb8d-411f-891e-55fe7ea8f8c6", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publ