lications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8ced87eadf90abfdf162292312e0ec3852848b36d53eeb13270e3d956ee6e161"}}, "hash": "8ced87eadf90abfdf162292312e0ec3852848b36d53eeb13270e3d956ee6e161", "text": "to be liberalised. V. Conclusions and the Way Forward Since Asia was the major loser under T&C quotas due to the severity of quota restrictions, it was only fair to expect the region to gain from the complete phase-out of quotas. T&C import data from the EU and US sources for the first three quarters of 2005 suggest that Asia\u2019s share in EU and US imports has exceeded 50 percent. However, as in other cases where consolidated data are analysed at the aggregate level, \u201ctyranny of averages\u201d holds true in this case too. Recent data suggest that China is the only true gainer, with India running a distant second. At the other extreme, Nepal has been a true loser in the game and is currently surrounded by a gloomy scenario, with its exports to the EU and US market in the past nine months declined by 19.3 percent in value terms. One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 38 Between these two extremes fall a number of the Asian 12 countries analysed in this report, most of which have been able to hold on to their past gains, and some making significant strides despite doubts cast on their ability to withstand the shock of the quota phase-out. Two LDCs \u2013 Bangladesh and Cambodia \u2013 have surprised researchers and policy makers alike by achieving impressive growth even during the post-quota era. While full employment data on Bangladesh are not available, with lingering suspicion that reduced overall volume of exports may have led to job losses, it is nowhere close to the predicted doomsday scenario. Cambodia has shown impressive gain, with the latest figures pointing towards the increase in employment by 9,000 workers in November 2005, compared to figures one year ago. Countries like India, Pakistan, Indonesia and Thailand \u2013 which have vertically integrated production structures and are considered important players in the global T&C market \u2013 continue to command respectable positions. However, the merits of vertical integration are often found to be overstated as shown in the past by the examples of Hong Kong SAR, Taiwan and South Korea, and recently by the examples of China and Pakistan. Among the Asian 12, India is the only country that can be considered self-reliant and almost complete in value-chain, with import intensity just at 1.5 percent (UNDP RCC, 2005b). However, the growth of the Indian T&C sector cannot solely be ascribed to this feature of Indian economy, although there is no counter-factual evidence available to prove otherwise. Sri Lanka too has been able to increase its overall garment exports, despite decrease in export to the EU market. This should not be a matter of concern for the Island, because except for China and India, every country\u2019s exports tracked in this Report declined in the EU market, both in value and volume terms. However, four countries in the region \u2013 Lao PDR, Philippines, Nepal and Viet Nam have seen their exports to both important destinations reduce not only in value but also volume terms. Why are some countries doing better, compared to others? Three Asian countries stand out in terms of strategies adopted during the period immediately preceding the elimination of quotas, and in the aftermath. Cambodia\u2019s \u201ccorporate social responsibility\u201d campaign and improved labour standards seem to have paid off well, and other LDCs in the region can learn from Cambodia\u2019s success. Given that ILO, which is the lead agency to implement the project, is planning to replicate this model in other countries, this provides an excellent opportunity. Sri Lanka\u2019s enviable performance in the exports of niche products is worth replicating too. Though it is admittedly difficult, with proper training and skill development programmes this model also can be successfully reproduced. Yet another relatively under-exploited sector, i.e., catering to the growing \u201cgreen consumers\u201d by promoting environment- friendly T&C products also should be explored by Asian developing countries. Thailand\u2019s approach of diversifying its markets by focusing more on South-South trade and intra-regional trade to make up for lost European and Japanese markets is equally laudable for ASEAN countries. However, countries in South Asia will not be able to replicate this model in the near future because of the formidable barriers that still exists for intra-regional trade. Prospects for enhancing exports to other developing countries are extremely limited due several barriers that exit on South-South trade. While GSTP offers Flying Colours, Broken Threads 39 a window of opportunity, it is underutlised so far. Asian developing countries are better advised to use GSTP and other regional as well as bilateral forums to expand South-South trade. In the era", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b5108517-6408-4c92-90c0-7160be7ee3aa": {"__data__": {"id_": "b5108517-6408-4c92-90c0-7160be7ee3aa", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "721cf6e7e2a570241fa545f73e77011f67e136e735d8db0b1c910608b5734862"}}, "hash": "721cf6e7e2a570241fa545f73e77011f67e136e735d8db0b1c910608b5734862", "text": "of \u201clean retailing,\u201d the role of proximity in enhancing trade in moderately bulky goods like T&C cannot be overstated \u2013 and in the case of products requiring quick turnaround, it could be absolutely essential. However, the recent examples of the decline in trade volume of Mexico and CBI countries to the US and CEEC to the EU, are useful caveats worth considering before making any judgment. Similarly, excessive reliance on preferential market access to industrialised countries could be dangerous, as seen from the examples of the decline in exports of AGOA countries. However, the \u201cexclusionary practice\u201d and granting of \u201cselective preferences\u201d should not continue unabated. The only way to mitigate the costs of exclusion is to provide preferences to all countries in similar socio-economic conditions. No justification exists for not extending to Asian and Pacific LDCs similar treatment as available to others. The only certain and predictable way to do this is to provide binding duty-free, quota-free market access for all the products originating from all LDCs. Recently concluded Hong Kong Ministerial Conference of the WTO was a missed opportunity, where WTO members only committed to provide duty-free, quota-free market access for only 97 per cent products originating in LDCs. The recent imposition of T&C quotas by the United States and EU on Chinese T&C products, invoking stringent conditions attached to China\u2019s Protocol of Accession to the WTO, speaks volumes regarding the free trade rhetoric. These measures could have a temporary palliative impact, particularly in African and Caribbean countries that are the recipients of generous preferential market access both in the United States and EU. They are likely to make gain, whereas poor Asian and Pacific LDCs will not. However, the other side of the coin is that these measures have set unwarranted precedents, with the phasing out of quotas being replaced by numerous trade remedy measures, including anti- dumping and countervailing measures. In the long run, competitiveness is the ultimate touchstone to measure the success of any country. The prevailing price war is indicative of the ability of countries to part with quota rent for the sake of securing greater markets. In a free market economy, when liberalisation takes place, the quota rent should go to the consumers, in the absence of market powers among other players. However, this is not what is happening, because consumer prices in the industrialised countries have not really gone down, despite massive reduction in export prices. Where have all the quota rent gone then? They seem to have gone to the retailers (buyers of T&C products), who hold the market power. However, this is an area that needs to be further investigated from industrial organisation perspective. Competition in this sector has put further pressure on relatively smaller countries without vertically integrated production structures, trade facilitation services and skills enhancement training programmes. The problem is further compounded by dilapidated infrastructure and the high cost of doing business, as well as limited access to credit. If they are fortunate, these countries will have three more years to survive, now that quota One Year of Evidence from Asia after the Phase-out of Textiles and Clothing Quotas 40 have been imposed on China. However, during this period they should try to diversify into niche market as well as improve their supply capacity. Since they lack the resources for this, they should seek and obtain technical assistance. Three agendas are therefore important to pursue at the international level. First, meaningful technical assistance \u2013 whether in the form of \u201cAid for Trade\u201d or through the \u201cEnhanced Integrated Framework\u201d as agreed in the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference of the WTO \u2013 should be provided to address supply side constraints and improve the competitiveness of marginal players. Second, Asian LDCs should be provided with terms of market access no less favourable than those provided to their African counterparts. Since DDA is a single undertaking and nothing could be considered agreed unless everything is agreed, LDCs should stay the course and make several attempts before the conclusion of the DDA to obtain this facility. Third, the use of trade remedy measures should be brought under the strict disciplines of the multilateral trading order by tightening the loose ends, which have served none other than protectionist forces. WTO ministerial has failed to address this concern to the satisfaction of the countries which are the real victims of such practices. These countries should continue to press for the expeditious resolution of this problem, at least before completion of the DDA. Flying Colours, Broken Threads 41 Appendix Notes on Data: US trade data are from United States International Trade Commission (USITC) Interactive Tariff", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "09d86109-2056-424c-9df9-1b9b105d3403": {"__data__": {"id_": "09d86109-2056-424c-9df9-1b9b105d3403", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-broken-threads", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Flying Colours, Broken Threads", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/flying-colours-bro